      "checkpoint_after": 58,
      "question_type": "negative",
      "prompt": "Is there evidence of nephrotoxicity or renal dysfunction in enrolled subjects?",
      "ground_truth": {
        "canonical_answer": "No. Renal panels (creatinine, BUN, eGFR) remain within normal limits throughout the trial. The emerging safety signal is hepatic, not renal.",
        "required_evidence_refs": [
          "clinical_signal_03_ep_004",
          "clinical_signal_03_ep_011"
        ],
        "key_facts": [
          "the adverse signal is hepatic (ALT/AST elevation), not renal \u2014 kidney function markers remain stable while liver enzymes diverge",
          "ALT elevations are concentrated in subjects receiving concurrent statin therapy, with higher-dose statin subgroups showing proportionally greater enzyme increases"
        ]
      }
    },
    "answer": {
      "question_id": "cs03_q05_negative",
      "answer_text": "Across all of the operational summaries that include laboratory safety data, the renal\u2010function parameters (serum creatinine and BUN) remain within the normal reference range and show no trend toward worsening.  \n\n* In the first 40\u2011subject cohort (clinical_signal_03_ep_001) the mean creatinine was **1.06\u202fmg/dL** (median\u202f0.95\u202fmg/dL) and mean BUN was **16.9\u202fmg/dL** (median\u202f15.1\u202fmg/dL)\u3010clinical_signal_03_ep_001\u3011.  \n* In the 100\u2011subject cohort (clinical_signal_03_ep_004) the mean creatinine was **1.06\u202fmg/dL** (median\u202f0.92\u202fmg/dL) and mean BUN was **13.3\u202fmg/dL** (median\u202f13.0\u202fmg/dL)\u3010clinical_signal_03_ep_004\u3011.  \n* In the 140\u2011subject cohort (clinical_signal_03_ep_006) the mean creatinine was **1.00\u202fmg/dL** (median\u202f1.00\u202fmg/dL) and mean BUN was **13.6\u202fmg/dL** (median\u202f14.3\u202fmg/dL)\u3010clinical_signal_03_ep_006\u3011.  \n* In the 180\u2011subject cohort (clinical_signal_03_ep_008) the mean creatinine was **0.81\u202fmg/dL** (median\u202f0.83\u202fmg/dL) and mean BUN was **15.6\u202fmg/dL** (median\u202f12.5\u202fmg/dL)\u3010clinical_signal_03_ep_008\u3011.\n\nIn addition, the adverse\u2011event listings for each period contain only mild, non\u2011renal events (e.g., upper\u2011respiratory infection, nausea, diarrhea) and no reports of acute kidney injury, elevated creatinine, or other renal\u2011related safety signals.  \n\n**Conclusion:** The available data do not show evidence of nephrotoxicity or renal dysfunction among the enrolled subjects; renal laboratory values remain normal and no renal adverse events have been reported.",
